Was Snap’s IPO underpriced?

US-based social media company Snap’s (previously known as Snapchat) public trading debut didn’t disappoint, much like several others from the tech industry. The company’s shares soared from its IPO price of $17 to $24.48 an increase of 44 per cent.What does having share prices jump by 40 per cent as soon as the bell rings indiacte? Quite simply, that the company could have sold shares for a higher price and raised much more money. Here is a look at stock price gains of internet companies on their first day of public trading. 
